  <!-- EXHIBIT 4 -->
  <div class="exhibit">
    <div class="exhibit-header">
      <div class="exhibit-tag">EXHIBIT 4</div>
      <div class="exhibit-line"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="exhibit-title">Research Notes</div>

    <div class="paper-card">
      <div class="card-label">Source 1 Notes</div>
      <div class="card-title">The Great Depression & the Rise of Totalitarianism</div>
      <ul>
        <li>The Great Depression started with the Stock Market Crash in 1929 and lasted through the 1930s, causing mass unemployment and poverty across Canada and the world.</li>
        <li>Unemployment in Canada reached about 27% at its worst — millions of people had no jobs and no income.</li>
        <li>Banks failed and families lost their savings. Businesses closed and international trade collapsed sharply.</li>
        <li>Many families had to rely on soup kitchens and government relief programs just to survive.</li>
        <li>The Prairie provinces suffered from drought and the Dust Bowl — crops failed completely and farmers lost everything.</li>
        <li>The Canadian government was slow to respond. Relief camps paid unemployed men only 20 cents a day in terrible conditions.</li>
        <li>Economic desperation made people across Europe angry and desperate, creating perfect conditions for extremist leaders to rise to power.</li>
        <li>When governments failed to fix the economy, people turned to strong leaders who promised order, jobs, and national greatness.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="source-footer">
        <strong>Source:</strong>
        <a href="https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/great-depression">https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/great-depression</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="paper-card">
      <div class="card-label">Source 2 Notes</div>
      <div class="card-title">How Totalitarian Governments Gained Power</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Fascism is a type of government where a dictator has total control, using extreme nationalism and military strength to dominate society.</li>
        <li>Adolf Hitler led the Nazi Party in Germany. He promised to fix the economy, restore national pride, and rebuild Germany's military after WWI losses.</li>
        <li>Hitler became Chancellor of Germany in 1933 and quickly dismantled democracy, removing political opponents and seizing total control.</li>
        <li>He used propaganda — posters, radio, and speeches — to control what people believed, spread hatred of Jewish people, and build loyalty to the Nazi Party.</li>
        <li>The Nuremberg Laws stripped Jewish people of their citizenship and rights, eventually leading to the Holocaust — the murder of six million Jewish people.</li>
        <li>Benito Mussolini rose to power in Italy in 1922 using nationalism, fear, and promises of a powerful nation.</li>
        <li>Francisco Franco took power in Spain after a brutal civil war, establishing another fascist dictatorship in Europe.</li>
        <li>In Japan, military leaders took control in the 1930s, promoted extreme loyalty to the emperor, and expanded Japan's empire through invasion.</li>
        <li>In Canada, intolerance also grew — Jewish, Asian, and Indigenous people were discriminated against and denied jobs during the Depression.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="source-footer">
        <strong>Sources:</strong>
        <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/world-war-ii-history">https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/world-war-ii-history</a>
        <a href="https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/adolf-hitler">https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/adolf-hitler</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="paper-card">
      <div class="card-label">Source 3 Notes</div>
      <div class="card-title">Canada's Role in World War II</div>
      <ul>
        <li>Canada declared war on Germany on September 10, 1939 — one week after Britain — showing loyalty to Britain while acting as an independent nation.</li>
        <li>Over one million Canadians served in the armed forces during WWII, fighting in Europe, North Africa, and the Pacific.</li>
        <li>The Royal Canadian Navy helped protect supply ships in the Battle of the Atlantic, fighting against German U-boat attacks throughout the war.</li>
        <li>The Dieppe Raid of 1942 was a major disaster — over 900 Canadian soldiers killed and nearly 2,000 captured. German defences were far stronger than expected.</li>
        <li>Lessons from Dieppe helped plan D-Day in June 1944. Canadians landed at Juno Beach as part of the massive Allied invasion of Nazi-occupied France.</li>
        <li>About 22,000 Japanese Canadians were forced into internment camps — a major example of wartime racism inside Canada itself.</li>
        <li>The war transformed Canada's economy. Factories switched to producing weapons and supplies, ending unemployment and raising wages across the country.</li>
        <li>Women entered the workforce in large numbers, permanently changing gender roles and expectations in Canadian society.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="source-footer">
        <strong>Sources:</strong>
        <a href="https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/second-world-war-wwii">https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/second-world-war-wwii</a>
        <a href="https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/dieppe-raid">https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/dieppe-raid</a>
        <a href="https://www.veterans.gc.ca/en/remembrance/wars-and-conflicts/second-world-war">https://www.veterans.gc.ca/en/remembrance/wars-and-conflicts/second-world-war</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="paper-card">
      <div class="card-label">Source 4 Notes</div>
      <div class="card-title">Key Battles & Technology</div>
      <ul>
        <li>The Battle of Britain (1940) — Germany tried to bomb Britain into surrender with air attacks. Britain's Royal Air Force held them off and prevented a German land invasion.</li>
        <li>Radar technology allowed Britain to detect German aircraft early, giving pilots time to respond — a crucial advantage that helped Britain survive.</li>
        <li>Hitler invaded the Soviet Union in 1941, breaking a non-aggression pact. Harsh winters and fierce Soviet resistance eventually stopped and pushed back Germany.</li>
        <li>The Battle of the Atlantic was the longest campaign of WWII. Canada's navy defended supply routes against German U-boats for the entire duration of the war.</li>
        <li>Allied scientists cracked Germany's Enigma code, allowing the Allies to read secret German military communications — a massive strategic advantage.</li>
        <li>Medical advances included battlefield blood transfusions and penicillin to treat infections, saving thousands of soldiers who would otherwise have died.</li>
        <li>The atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima (August 6) and Nagasaki (August 9) in 1945, ending the war in the Pacific and changing warfare forever.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="source-footer">
        <strong>Sources:</strong>
        <a href="https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/world-war-ii-history">https://www.history.com/topics/world-war-ii/world-war-ii-history</a>
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="paper-card">
      <div class="card-label">Source 5 Notes</div>
      <div class="card-title">Long-Term Impacts of World War II</div>
      <ul>
        <li>WWII was the deadliest conflict in human history — between 70 and 85 million people died, most of them civilians.</li>
        <li>The Holocaust resulted in the systematic murder of six million Jewish people and millions of others by the Nazi regime.</li>
        <li>The United Nations was created in 1945 to promote international peace, cooperation, and human rights so a conflict like WWII would never happen again.</li>
        <li>The political map of the world changed completely — empires collapsed, new countries formed, and Germany was split into democratic West Germany and communist East Germany.</li>
        <li>The Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union shaped global politics for decades, with both sides building massive armies and nuclear weapons.</li>
        <li>The Marshall Plan provided billions in U.S. aid to rebuild Western Europe, restart economies, and stop the spread of communism.</li>
        <li>Canada emerged stronger and more independent, with a booming economy and a much greater role in international affairs.</li>
        <li>The Nuremberg Trials held Nazi leaders accountable for war crimes and crimes against humanity, creating new principles in international law still used today.</li>
        <li>Women who proved themselves in wartime workplaces helped spark future movements for gender equality and women's rights around the world.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="source-footer">
        <strong>Sources:</strong>
        <a href="https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/second-world-war-wwii">https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/second-world-war-wwii</a>
